I contacted Rolls-Royce Motor Cars Boston last week to schedule routine maintenance for my 2006 Rolls-Royce Phantom. Since the dealership is about 100 miles away, I asked about transportation options. The representative I spoke with, Amanda, offered to check with management to see if a complimentary pickup was possible and would get back to me by the end of the day. I did not receive a return call.

Over the next several days, I left multiple messages and made follow-up calls. When I reached her again, she did not remember our previous conversation at first, and after I refreshed her memory, she said the vehicle was too old for a courtesy pickup. I then asked for a quote for a paid pickup service. She told me she would speak with management and call me back that day. Again, I received no call.

I made one more attempt and left another message, but as of today, I still have not received a return call.

I am disappointed with the lack of follow-through and communication, especially given the expectations that typically accompany the Rolls-Royce name. I hope the dealership will review this experience and improve responsiveness for future customers.

Update December 8, 2025:

I received a follow-up call from the service manager after posting my review, and I appreciate that he took the time to reach out. He explained that the department had been short-staffed due to his attendance at a manufacturer conference.

On my initial call, Amanda did mention that she needed to speak with management before giving me an answer, and I appreciated that transparency. The concern was not that she needed guidance; it was that she assured me she would call back the same day, and no call ever came. After several additional attempts on my part, I still received no follow-up.

While I appreciate the courtesy of the manager’s call, the explanation did not fully resolve the underlying issue. Even if short-staffed, a quick message acknowledging the delay or letting me know a decision would have to wait until management returned would have set clear expectations. Instead, the lack of communication over several days made the process more difficult than it needed to be.

The follow-up call did confirm that the challenge was not simply workload but a breakdown in communication and follow-through. I hope this feedback helps the department strengthen those areas going forward.

At this time, I believe my original rating remains accurate based on the full experience.

I like to believe most people are good and honorable, but I found neither at this dealership. It was a disappointing reminder of why I hadn’t purchased from a dealership in 8 years.

The car I chose had a sticker price of $23,777. After taxes and “document fees,” the salesman presented me a written quote of $26,267—the higher end of my $28,000 budget, but still manageable. Confident in the purchase, I even went ahead and bought insurance for the car.

That’s when the circus began. We arrived at 4:00 p.m. and were kept waiting for hours. Not called back until 7:45 p.m., nearly an hour after closing, exhausted and ready to sign. And that’s exactly what they were banking on.

When the finance manager finally slid the paperwork across the desk, my pen was literally on the page when I noticed the numbers. That $26,000 “deal”? Suddenly it had ballooned to over $30,000. No explanation. No disclosure. Just “sign here.”

And why? Because they had quietly tacked on thousands in worthless warranties and add-ons I never asked for. Things no one bothered to explain—just slipped in, hoping I’d be too tired or too trusting to notice. The only comments I heard were, “oh, we have a warranty on it” and “we’ll throw in the gap on us!” Throw in? No—sneak in.

When I called out this deceit, the manager insisted he’d given me a “great deal.” In what world does a $23,000 car magically becoming a $30,000 purchase qualify as a deal? To make matters worse, when I said no one told me the price increase, he brushed it off with, “I told you what the monthly payments would be.” As if anyone would assume a $26,000 quote somehow meant a $30,000 loan.

This dealership didn’t just lose a sale—they proved exactly why people hate buying cars. If you value your money, your sanity, and your dignity, stay far, far away.
Shame on you.

We recently visited the Four Seasons for afternoon tea and, unfortunately, the experience was disappointing and fell well below the standard expected of a five-star hotel.

Throughout the experience, no additional hot water for the tea was offered, which is a basic expectation for afternoon tea service. Furthermore, when we enquired about the possibility of a small savoury top-up, we were informed that this would be chargeable. This is not standard practice at most afternoon tea venues and is particularly surprising at a hotel of the Four Seasons’ calibre.

Overall, the experience did not meet the expectations associated with a five-star establishment. We hope this feedback is taken constructively and helps improve the service for future guests.

Unfortunately, these are the last good things I can say about this dealership.

Immediately after purchase, the vehicle threw a check engine light for a faulty thermostat that needed to be replaced. We took the vehicle to a Mazda Dealership as directed by our "warranty", only to find that the thermostat repair would not be covered by this program, nor would they cover any of the other service items that the vehicle needed as recommended by the inspection. This caused an additional out of pocket expense that we were not expecting based on the sale of our extended warranty coverage. For an additional $3,000 on top of the purchase price of the vehicle, the expectation was set that repairs would be heavily discounted or paid entirely by this program.

After this experience and paying for the repairs out of pocket, we went to attempt to cancel this warranty. This is a process that can only be initiated by the dealer, so we needed to reach out to PDX Motors directly. We contacted PDX Motors to cancel this warranty in writing on 4/9/25. PDX Motors sent the refund for this warranty to our lender on 5/30/25. From the time that the warranty was originally requested to be canceled to the time the refund was issued took nearly 2 months, and countless calls and emails that went unanswered. Had I not have continuously followed up, we may still be waiting. When speaking with the warranty company, they confirmed cancelation on 4/25/25 and confirmed that they issue payment within 5 business days.

Lastly, while waiting for this warranty refund to be issued, the vehicle caught fire during a road trip while stopping for gas. The car burned completely to the ground without warning and was a total loss through insurance. While I don't necessarily blame PDX Motors for this, it certainly doesn't inspire buying confidence when coupled with check engine lights and other hidden repairs being needed.

If you are going to purchase a vehicle from these people, make sure you get an independent inspection. I went against my better judgement, skipped one with this vehicle, and quite literally got burned.

Unfortunately, as I was leaving, one of the receptionists gave me clear attitude when I said goodbye, signaling she was displeased that I had offered feedback to her coworker. It was uncomfortable and unprofessional. I stepped outside, sat in my car, and debated whether I should let it go or report the behavior. I decided to go back in. As I re-entered, the same receptionist walked out and again gave me attitude, which led me to feel even more frustration. The situation felt unnecessary and unprofessional.

I then asked for contact information for the doctor to formally share my experience, but the staff did not have a clear method for connecting with her. At that moment, the original staff member I had spoken with told me she had actually forgotten to take my measurements, so I needed to sit back down to complete a step that should have been done earlier.

Overall, the exam with Dr. Shah was wonderful, but the checkout and front-desk experience left me feeling uncomfortable and dismissed. I’m sharing this in hopes that it can be addressed so future visits reflect the same professionalism and care that Dr. Shah provides.

I purchased a new Audi S6 Avant e-tron (2025) from the authorized dealer Porsche Graz-Kärntnerstraße. Immediately after delivery, serious defects appeared – in particular, the repeated error message "High-voltage electrical system: malfunction," which prevents the vehicle from starting and the charging ports from opening, as well as the sudden failure of the left digital exterior mirror while driving.
These defects pose an acute risk to the health and life of the vehicle's occupants. If the digital mirror suddenly fails while driving, safe maneuvering or reacting to traffic is impossible. The risk of an accident is real.
Despite several visits to authorized Audi workshops, the defects persist. Furthermore, the service employees cannot specify exactly which problems the planned software updates are actually intended to resolve, which gives the impression of a trial-and-error approach.
This approach is unacceptable to me as a customer. With a new vehicle, you expect a functioning and safe product – not an immature experiment.
I am seriously considering withdrawing from the purchase agreement, but have initially granted a reasonable period of grace. As a customer-friendly solution, I prefer a buyback from Audi AG or, in the worst case, a replacement vehicle without defects.
Unfortunately, I cannot currently recommend Audi or this dealer. It seems that immature vehicles are deliberately sold – with all the consequences for the end customer.
My trust in Audi is currently zero. When switching from another premium brand with three letters, I had significantly higher expectations. Instead of a premium experience, I experienced a rude collision with reality.
If anyone is interested in video recordings of the documented defects (also in connection with media publication), I would be happy to provide them upon request.

No one informed me that I would have to wait 15 minutes for the roll, or that it wasn’t freshly baked but frozen. When it finally arrived, the kids were excited—it looked nice with frosting and some fruit on top. But the moment we took the first bite, we realized it was hard as a rock and very dry—impossible to cut with a fork.

To me, it felt like a three-day-old pastry that had just been reheated and topped with fresh frosting. I wanted to say something right away, but there was a long queue at the bar. I didn’t want my kids to eat it, but they were too hungry so they ate half of each. When I eventually spoke to the staff, they told me the roll wasn’t old—it had been baked, frozen, and possibly overheated. They offered another cake as compensation, but we didn’t have time and didn’t want anything else to eat after that so we left.
Since we paid 17 euros for two coffees and two cinnamon rolls, I felt I had to share this experience for future customers. And to the manager and staff: I’m not here to teach you how to handle these situations, but the least you could’ve done was cancel the order and offer a refund.

Also, let’s be honest: a reheated cinnamon roll can never compare to a freshly baked one. I wonder—have you ever actually tried the cinnamon roll you’re selling for 4.5 euros? I have avoided writing this review for years because the experience is still painful to think about, but I feel it’s important to share.

Years ago, my dog was diagnosed with a heart murmur by Dr. Corinne Lemay. As many pet owners know, a murmur can be an early warning sign of heart disease, and early referral to a cardiologist can make a meaningful difference. Unfortunately, Dr. Lemay never recommended a cardiology referral at that stage. Instead, we waited until my dog was already in heart failure before a referral was finally made; long after she could have been evaluated for early-intervention medications that might have helped delay the progression.

Throughout the months that followed, I often felt dismissed when I asked questions or expressed concerns. Any time I asked something heart-related, I was met with, “I’m not a vet cardiologist, so I cannot answer your heart questions,” delivered in a tone that made me reluctant to ask anything further. Because of that, during appointments I only brought up issues unrelated to her heart; not because I was in denial, but because I was trying to respect the boundaries she set.

One appointment stands out clearly: I brought my dog in because I suspected an upper respiratory issue (she was later diagnosed with asthma). Dr. Lemay looked at me and said, “You know what I think? I think you’re in denial that your dog is in heart failure.” It was one of the most hurtful comments I have ever heard from a veterinarian.

I was not in denial, I was living in constant panic, managing an exhaustive medication regimen (Flovent inhaler, Hydrocodone, Prednisone, nausea meds, Torsemide, Sildenafil, Spironolactone, Benazepril, Vetmedin, vitamins, and more), monitoring her symptoms 24/7, and doing everything in my power to keep her comfortable. I rarely slept. I never left her alone. I even risked my job once by bringing her to work because I refused to let her struggle without me. The suggestion that I was somehow ignoring her condition was not only inaccurate, it was cruel.

That comment, combined with the lack of early referral and the overall dismissiveness, was the moment I knew I could no longer bring my dog back to Manchester Animal Hospital. I needed compassionate, proactive care, and unfortunately, I did not receive that here.

I wish I could write a different review. I wish this experience had been supportive, collaborative, and respectful. But it wasn’t, and sharing this is the only way I can help other pet owners advocate for their companions.

I was disheartened with the lack of empathy about my needs. You may be a Dr. but I am not making up my health problems to take a very common anxiety medication. Escitalopram. It’s not an addictive medication and I have a mental health diagnosis… that is painfully clear to renew my prescription.

Decent mental health therapists, physical therapists, pharmacy and dental hygienists next door but I the dentist is a different entity. I never had issues with scheduling, health insurance, timely appointments, payments or any technical issues, the MyChart app is great. Staff are friendly or at least somewhat short and neutral haha.
I noticed my experience here generally revolved around Drs. meandering around an issue when I’m looking for you to tell me the next step, a referral, or tell me what information do you need to confirm my diagnosis? I was treated like a child, complaining, ok goodbye. Please listen to your patients attentively and offer solutions, please do not dismiss patients so quickly.
I am choosing to not return here, and I am saddened as this is a convenient location around a lovely forested area in Beacon Hill. I’ve seen other patients give good reviews so maybe still worth visiting!

I'm surprised to see all the hate on here for Dr. Kim Carney. I've never experienced this 'attitude' from her that other people are seeing. She's always been pleasant and helpful to me. I have diabetes, arthritis, high cholesterol, and other chronic conditions so my appts usually take some time and she's never been rushed or rude to me about it. I can understand frustration on her part at times because they way overbook here and it takes at least 2 months to get an appointment. Everybody has bad days, including doctors and I suppose people only do reviews to point out the negative (myself included). Anyways, I've decided to change clinics to Fransiscan because/ A. My PCP Kim left the clinic/ B. A lot of the staff there, including at the pharmacy, have very heavy accents and trying to understand them over the phone is a frustrating situation. I spent 30 minutes on the phone with their pharmacy once JUST trying to see if my meds were ready and the lady i was talking to spoke very broken English. Finally the pharmacist got on to help me. I know this isn't their fault but I dont have time to sit on the phone while someone is trying to learn the language./ C. This place is not clean, it's very rundown/ and D. They make having a chronic illness even worse than it already is. Just dealing with their ineptitude is like having a second full-time job. There was one, ONE, blissful year that a saint worked in the billing department that made sure my account was handled correctly. I am part of a financial assistance program through the pharmaceutical company that provides the drug I need for MS and every month (except the 12 aforementioned blissful ones) I have had to call and make sure they send the post-insurance remainder to Biogen, and every month they don't do it. Which eventually leads me to being sent to collections, which then leads me to reaching out to Biogen (who has been excellent BTW) to confirm that I didn't somehow get kicked out of their financial assistance program and confirm that Virginia Mason hasn't filed a claim with them, which then leads me to calling Virginia Mason Billing to ask them to file a claim with Biogen....which may or may not happen by the time the next invoice rolls around. And repeat that over and over again every month for 10 years. Oh and the newest thing is that I'm still getting multiple thousands of dollars invoices but Biogen has sent them the checks, they've cashed them and they are still invoicing me saying it hasn't been paid AND sending me to collections! Then they ask me to just be patient. Also, since they were bought by the religious health organization "Franciscan Health" things have only gotten worse. Came here today on a guest pass. I was planning on signing up for a membership after today’s visit. Unfortunately, there are quite a few aspects that need improving before I’d do so.

Positives:
-The two staff members working at reception were very friendly and helpful.
-I loved the layout of the weights areas with semi-private “alcoves” to work out in.
-The old school, industrial architecture and exposed brick is very cool.
-The whole facility is very spacious and didn’t feel crowded at all despite quite a few people being there.

Areas for improvement:
-The men’s sauna (one of the main reasons I’d want to join) was barely warm due to the poorly installed glass door that has a large gap. A few members in there said they had complained about it, but it still hadn’t been fixed.
-The sauna had a clump of disgusting hair on the floor; a member mentioned it had been there for multiple days.
-The steam room was out of service. Talking to members, apparently it’s been like this for over a month due to a malfunctioning component.
-The general cleanliness of the main men’s locker room wasn’t great. Dirty floor, showers, etc.

If management addresses these issues, I would love to become a member and update this to a more positive review.

Weirdly exploitative experience tarnishing otherwise great gym. I pay the rather steep $155/month membership just to play basketball here because they're the only indoor basketball court in the downtown area. They just announced renovations to their indoor basketball court for 2-3 months from now through October.

Here's where it gets weird. You'd think that since we can't use the court anymore because they initiated renovations on a court that was totally fine, they could put a free pause on our memberships for the period. But no, in the fine print of the contract, "The Club will not reduce or suspend dues during the time when the facilities are not available."

So my options are to
1) Be billed $50 per month to freeze my membership (1/3rd of the regular monthly fee) to NOT use the gym, or
2) Give 30 days notice of cancellation, pay another $155 for the 30 days, and then pay $250+ to rejoin when the court is done with renovations.

Even if it's in the fine print, this doesn't feel right on principle. It's not a couple day repair. It's bleeding your members for months while you do a voluntary renovations. I actually really liked this gym, the front desk is always very helpful and welcoming. I hate that SAC is providing negative value to their basketball members just to make a few hundred dollars while doing a renovation we didn't ask for.

Dark, strange, and wildly overpriced.

This is easily the most unjustifiably expensive gym I’ve ever been to. It’s a basic, small, bare-bones facility charging prices that compete with Equinox — and delivering nowhere near the value.

Yes, it’s clean. That may be because no one seems to be there and it's too dark to see anything. The space is small, the equipment selection is limited, and even basic lifting amenities are missing (no chalk allowed — even for deadlifts). There are racks and machines, but nothing remotely special or premium.

The amenities are borderline nonexistent. There is effectively no proper shower setup (a single shower, no soap), no towels, and no sense that members are getting anything beyond the most minimal offering.

The atmosphere is honestly one of the worst parts. It’s so dark it’s soporific — like working out inside a dark, dark nightclub. The lighting is almost entirely purple and red, which makes the space feel more like an empty lounge than a gym. It’s distracting, unpleasant, and actively makes you feel tired rather than energized.

For the price, this place should be exceptional. Instead, it’s cramped, oddly lit, poorly equipped, and wildly overpriced. I genuinely don’t understand who this is for — but given how empty it was, I may not be alone.

Too bad.

Update: After I posted this review, management contacted me offering free day passes while asking if I would remove it. I declined. Reviews exist so people can understand what a place is actually like, and I’m not interested in changing an honest review in exchange for perks. Potential members deserve transparency.

Was DENIED Yellow Fever vaccine for my 15 month old son because he got red bumpy cheeks the very first time he had eggs months ago and never had a reaction since.

We live downtown San Francisco and do not have a car. I called so many places that did not have the yellow fever vaccine in stock or we would not be able to get an appointment in time for the 10 day incubation period for the vaccine to be considered valid.

I was able to make an appointment here  at the SFO medical clinic. I filled out the paperwork and was honest for the question that asked if my son had an egg allergy and I just said, “maybe” thinking back to that very first time he had eggs.

The nurse came out into the lobby and discussed with me that if he truly does have an egg allergy that the yellow fever vaccine can be “detrimental.” I told her I would consult with my husband and get back. After talking with my husband and searching through AI, we decided that our son would be OK.

I let the nurse know that I wanted to proceed with the vaccine, but at that point, she told me she did not feel comfortable administering it and did not want to risk losing her license. She said if I could get a note from a pediatrician saying that he is not allergic to eggs and send that to her that she would be willing to administer the shot.

Imagine being a young mom traveling alone and adding more barriers.

I would have to make an appointment with his pediatrician, have them make a referral to a pediatric allergy specialist, and from there they confirm or deny that he does not have an egg allergy. And then I would return all the way back to the San Francisco International Airport with the documentation showing that he does not have an egg allergy in order to receive the vaccine or that he does and receive some type of vaccine exemption form.

Today is August 6 and we leave August 10. The country that requires the vaccine we enter on August 18.

Can you guess what I’m going to do when I get home today after my travels on BART and bus? I’m going to make my son eggs just to remind myself that I’m not crazy and he does NOT have an egg allergy.

This is what I get for being honest for answering, “maybe”: more travel complications, more stress, and a rescheduled appointment in Oakland.

What does this clinic get out of the matter? A 1 star review.

UPDATE: Added the picture of my son eating eggs upon getting home and guess what?! He’s FINE!!! So if your child had ONE MILD REACTION upon first eating eggs, ANSWER THAT YOUR CHILD DOES NOT HAVE AN EGG ALLERGY! If you’re honest, the nurse will think she’s risking her livelihood administering the shot.
